  <section>
    <title>Prerequisites</title>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Java 7</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Release 2.1 of GeneSEZ will require Java 7 to run. The 
          older release 2.0 and 1.7 will work with Java 5.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Eclipse</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>GeneSEZ is designed as an eclipse bundle so we 
          recommend to use the eclipse ide. However there exist other 
          ways to get GeneSEZ running.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>Eclipse Plug-In Dependencies</title>
    <para>GeneSEZ has the following dependencies to plug-ins from the 
    eclipse modeling project:</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry id="org.genesez.dependency.emf">
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Eclipse Modeling Framework 
        (EMF)</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <variablelist>
            <para>You need at least the <emphasis>Runtime + End-User 
            Tools</emphasis> (p2 identifier: <literal>
            org.eclipse.emf.feature.group</literal>) in Version 
            <literal>2.3.x</literal> or higher. We recommend the latest 
            version.</para>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Homepage</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/emf/">http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/emf/</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Eclipse Update Site</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/emf/updates/releases/">http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/emf/updates/releases/</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry id="org.genesez.dependency.uml">
        <term><emphasis role="bold">EMF UML</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>You need at least the <emphasis>UML2 End-User 
          Features</emphasis> (p2 identifier: <literal>
          org.eclipse.uml2.feature.group</literal>) in Version <literal>
          2.1.x</literal> or higher. We recommend the latest 
          version.</para>
          <para>This plug-in depends on the 
          <xref linkend="org.genesez.dependency.emf"/>, so ensure you 
          choose a compatible version!</para>
          <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Homepage</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/mdt/?project=uml2">http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/mdt/?project=uml2</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Eclipse Update Site</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/mdt/updates/releases/">http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/mdt/updates/releases/</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry id="org.genesez.dependency.mwe">
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Modeling Workflow (Engine) (MWE and 
        optionally MWE2)</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>The <emphasis>MWE SDK</emphasis> (p2 identifier: 
          <literal>org.eclipse.emf.mwe.sdk.feature.group</literal>) is 
          a good choice. You can optionally install MWE2 (p2 
          identifier: <literal>
          org.eclipse.emf.mwe2.runtime.sdk.feature.group</literal> and 
          <literal>
          org.eclipse.emf.mwe2.language.sdk.feature.group</literal>), 
          it&apos;s based on MWE and provides a textual language to 
          specify transformation chains so you don&apos;t have to use 
          the XML syntax MWE provides. GeneSEZ should work with any 
          release version but we recommend the latest one.</para>
          <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Homepage</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/emft/?project=mwe">http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/emft/?project=mwe</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Eclipse Update Site</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/emft/updates/releases/">http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/emft/updates/releases/</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry id="org.genesez.dependency.xpand">
        <term><emphasis role="bold">XPand</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>The <emphasis>Xpand SDK</emphasis> (p2 identifier: 
          <literal>org.eclipse.xpand.sdk.feature.group</literal>) is a 
          good choice. GeneSEZ should work with any release versions 
          but we recommend the latest one.</para>
          <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Homepage</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/m2t/?project=xpand">http://www.eclipse.org/modeling/m2t/?project=xpand</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Eclipse Update Site</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>
                <ulink url="http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/m2t/updates/releases/">http://download.eclipse.org/modeling/m2t/updates/releases/</ulink></para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
    <para>Note that <emphasis role="bold">Release 1.7</emphasis> does 
    <emphasis>not</emphasis> depend on 
    <xref linkend="org.genesez.dependency.mwe"/> and 
    <xref linkend="org.genesez.dependency.xpand"/>. Instead is has a 
    dependency to <ulink url="http://openarchitectureware.org/">
    openArchitectureWare</ulink>. You will need at least the 
    <emphasis>core</emphasis>, <emphasis>plugins</emphasis>, 
    <emphasis>libraries</emphasis> and <emphasis>uml2 
    adapter</emphasis> in the latest version <literal>4.3.1</literal>. 
    <emphasis>openArchitectureWare</emphasis> depends on 
    <xref linkend="org.genesez.dependency.mwe" xreflabel="Modeling Workflow"/>
     and <xref linkend="org.genesez.dependency.uml"/> so make sure you 
    have compatible versions installed!</para>
  </section>
  <section id="org.genesez.installation">
    <title>Installation</title>
    <para>There are a couple of different ways how you can install 
    GeneSEZ:</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Download a GeneSEZ Eclipse 
        Distribution</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>You just <link linkend="org.genesez.download">
          download</link> one of our GeneSEZ-Eclipse distributions, 
          unpack it and try GeneSEZ. You do <emphasis>not</emphasis> 
          need to install GeneSEZ nor any of its dependencies, all you 
          need is already there!</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Install using Eclipe Update 
        Manager</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>You install GeneSEZ using its 
          <link linkend="org.genesez.updatesite">updatesite</link>. In 
          case you don&apos;t know how to install bundles into eclipse 
          you will find enough tutorials on the internet, e.g. 
          <ulink url="http://www.vogella.de/articles/Eclipse/article.html#plugin_installation">
          this by Lars Vogel</ulink>.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Lazy Install</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>If you feel lucky you can just copy the contents of the 
          <literal>dropins</literal> folder of one of our 
          <link linkend="org.genesez.download">GeneSEZ Eclipse 
          Distributions</link> into the <literal>dropins</literal> 
          folder of your eclipse installation. This folder contains 
          GeneSEZ and all its dependencies and it should work in most 
          cases. You can find more information about 
          <emphasis>p2</emphasis> and the <literal>dropins</literal> 
          folder 
          <ulink url="http://wiki.eclipse.org/Equinox_p2_Getting_Started#Dropins">
          here</ulink>.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>Workspace Configuration</title>
    <para>There are two things to consider about workflow configuration 
    when working with GeneSEZ.</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><emphasis role="bold">Xtend/Xpand Metamodel 
        Contributors</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Xtend and Xpand can use arbitrary meta models. This 
          setting specifies which are activated and in which order they 
          are used. You can change this settings by going to <literal>
          Window » Preferences</literal> and select the entry <literal>
          Xtend/Xpand</literal>. You should activate the following and 
          place them into the follwing order:</para>
          <orderedlist>
            <listitem>
              <para>UML2 Profiles</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
              <para>EMF Metamodels</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
              <para>JavaBeans Metamodel</para>
            </listitem>
          </orderedlist>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry id="org.genesez.encoding">
        <term><emphasis role="bold">File Encoding</emphasis></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>The syntax of Xpand has some special characters often 
          causing encoding problems. GeneSEZ uses <literal>
          UTF-8</literal> as default encoding and you should ensure 
          that every <emphasis>Xtend</emphasis>, 
          <emphasis>Xpand</emphasis> and <emphasis>Check</emphasis> 
          script you develop as customization is <literal>
          UTF-8</literal> encoded. Eclipse uses for each file the 
          <emphasis>workspace default encoding</emphasis> as default 
          which is usually to <literal>UTF-8</literal> under linux but 
          under windows otherwise!</para>
          <para>You can change the encoding settings on 
          <emphasis>workspace</emphasis>, <emphasis>project</emphasis>, 
          <emphasis>folder</emphasis> and <emphasis>file</emphasis> 
          level.</para>
          <variablelist>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>File</term>
              <term>Folder</term>
              <term>Project</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>Right click on the file/folder/project, select 
                <literal>Properties</literal>, select the entry 
                <literal>Resource</literal> and in the group <literal>
                Text file encoding</literal> you can specify the file 
                encoding.</para>
                <para>For folders you specify the default encoding for 
                each file in the folder. For projects the default 
                encoding for each file of the project.</para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
            <varlistentry>
              <term>Workspace</term>
              <listitem>
                <para>Go to <literal>Window » Preferences</literal> and 
                select the entry <literal>General » 
                Workspace</literal>. In the group <literal>Text file 
                encoding</literal> you can set the <emphasis>workspace 
                default encoding</emphasis>.</para>
              </listitem>
            </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </section>
